Welcome to Wall Power, finally back in these United States. I=E2=80=99m Mar=
ion Maneker=E2=80=94ready to tell you about my Parisian sojourn.

Before embarking on this fortnight abroad, we set out to answer two questio=
ns. First, would it be London or Paris that proved to be ascendant, both in=
 art fairs and auctions? Second, might the art market reverse its momentum?=
 As it turns out, we were asking the wrong questions.

The pendulum has already switched directions. In Paris, I ran into a major =
private dealer at the Tom Wesselmann retrospective who was all smiles, repo=
rting that many galleries had better sales in London than expected. That=E2=
=80=99s something I heard in a number of places. This same dealer also felt=
 that a good showing in Paris=E2=80=94both at the fair and at the manicured=
 auctions here=E2=80=94would set the table for November. If those
sales deliver, we could be in for a new market narrative.

Before getting into what happened at Art Basel Paris, however, let=E2=80=99=
s briefly discuss where we should be turning our attention. Indeed, what=E2=
=80=99s going on in London is particular to the London market, which is sti=
ll absorbing the aftershocks of Brexit. Yet it remains a major art center, =
with numerous great museums, a recent history of strong production by local=
 artists, and an extensive gallery infrastructure. Also, American buyers ar=
e currently sustaining the market. So London plays an obvious role; there=
=E2=80=99s a special relationship in art, too. That means the better questi=
on isn=E2=80=99t whether London can withstand the ascent of Paris, but whet=
her Paris can efficiently consolidate the European art trade via larger and=
 more efficiently centralized sales at the auction houses. More on that on =
Tuesday. Now I want to tell you more about Art Basel in Paris.

