The Nahmads=E2=80=99 booth featured one of Joan Mir=C3=B3=E2=80=99s series =
of constellation paintings. (Another in the series got pride of place at th=
e end of the surrealism show at the Centre Pompidou.) The Nahmads were adam=
ant that the painting, which had been bought at auction seven years before =
for $31 million, was not for sale. Meanwhile, Hauser & Wirth conspicuously =
displayed Kazimir Malevich=E2=80=99s Suprematism, 18th Construction in the =
middle of their booth, which was bought at auction in 2015 for $33.7 millio=
n, and which had also been brought to the fair with no advance notice. One =
prominent collector told me the best picture at the fair was Landau=E2=80=
=99s Wassily Kandinsky painting, Murnau mit Kirche II, which the dealer bou=
ght for nearly $45 million early last year and repeatedly deflected questio=
ns about price with vague
numbers (well into the high eight-figures) until this week, when the work w=
as on the stand but =E2=80=9Cnot for sale.=E2=80=9D One would expect this k=
ind of dealer behavior at Art Basel=E2=80=99s apex event in Switzerland; th=
at it was happening in Paris was a sign that galleries were going all-out t=
o impress potential buyers, and to build anticipation for next year.

And yet, perhaps even more important for Paris was the fact that the city=
=E2=80=99s museums and art foundations pulled out all the stops to mount a =
wide variety of shows. The best of them, according to Bloomberg=E2=80=99s J=
ames Tarmy, was the knockout retrospective of 92-year-old Colombian artist =
Olga de Amaral, held at the Cartier Foundation for Contemporary Art, which =
has been housed for 30 years in a glass-box Jean Nouvel building deep in th=
e 14th arrondissement. (It will move to another Jean Nouvel-designed buildi=
ng in a more central location across from the Louvre next year.) There were=
 also two
encyclopedic surveys: one of Arte Povera at Fran=C3=A7ois Pinault=E2=80=99s=
 Bourse de Commerce; and the exhaustive, and a little bit exhausting, 100th=
 anniversary of surrealism show at the Centre Pompidou.

The Arte Povera show had numerous great pieces, but depending on your taste=
 or point of view, just as many or more baffling works=E2=80=94although it =
also reveals the extent of Pinault=E2=80=99s holdings, which is staggering.=
 Meanwhile, the surrealism show lacked a clear thesis. There was so much wo=
rk by so many different artists that it was difficult to see the forest for=
 the trees. At the Mus=C3=A9e d=E2=80=99Orsay, there was a long-overdue cel=
ebration of the art of Gustave Caillebotte, a painter better known to histo=
ry for his financial and moral support of his impressionist peers than as t=
he deeply modern artist that he was. The focus on Caillebotte was certainly=
 a fitting way to mark the 150th anniversary in the city where impressionis=
m was born.

I cannot
leave the topic of museum shows without mentioning the surprise show of the=
 week: Jackson Pollock at the Picasso Museum. It turned out to be an instru=
ctive meditation on the influence of Picasso and his surrealist works on Po=
llock and his circle in the 1930s, when they were feeling their way toward =
the breakthrough moments of abstract expressionism.

Paris vs. Basel

In short, Horowitz had many reasons to feel chuffed. An art fair, after all=
, is about more than just selling art. For galleries, the sales matter, but=
 they also benefit from participating in a great, exclusive fair, which thi=
s certainly was. Many galleries participate in Art Basel in Hong Kong or Mi=
ami in the hopes that, over time, they might earn the right to show in Base=
l. This year, the Paris fair had 195 participating galleries, and a third o=
f them operate spaces in France.

Of course, for collectors, a fair like Art Basel is about far more than goi=
ng home with an invoice for a new painting or sculpture. It is an experienc=
e=E2=80=94part reunion, part chance to measure one=E2=80=99s status, part e=
ntertainment. And for new collectors, it=E2=80=99s an education, a way to t=
ake in a lot of art in a short period of time, to train the eye and learn t=
he
landscape and lingo. But you=E2=80=99ll always feel like an outsider if you=
 don=E2=80=99t buy, because buying art is what gets you invited to the dinn=
ers and the parties.

