This was the third year Art Basel has operated in Paris, but it was the fir=
st year that the fair has been called Art Basel. It was also the first time=
 the fair has been held at the Grand Palais, which is more prominently loca=
ted than the temporary space near the Eiffel Tower used in recent years. Bu=
t I was left wondering what Art Basel can do to top this year, and whether =
the French cultural establishment can continue to raise its level of offeri=
ngs. There=E2=80=99s also the question of what the success of Art Basel Par=
is will mean for the company=E2=80=99s other fairs. Many American collector=
s would prefer to spend a week in Paris over a few days in Basel. One Midwe=
stern collector told me he had arrived with his daughters and their spouses=
 planning to spend a diary-packed week in Paris. But they did not buy anyth=
ing at the fair=E2=80=94at least, not anything
serious. Horowitz would probably prefer that he go to Basel to buy and Pari=
s to have fun, anyway. But will he?

And what about Miami? With everyone gathered here in Paris in October, how =
important will it be to head to Miami in December? I spoke to a gallerist f=
rom Switzerland who did Frieze, and who held a show in their Paris apartmen=
t that involved a series of dinners and cocktail parties to consider the wo=
rks. This gallery does eight art fairs a year, but this gallerist was looki=
ng forward to Miami, too. So maybe everything=E2=80=99s all right in the ar=
t fair ecosystem.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

An experienced British dealer who had done many F.I.A.C. art fairs in the G=
rand Palais pulled me aside outside of the fair, at a place I can no longer=
 remember, to offer an observation: Although Art Basel was much better, the=
 food was still terrible. I told him that I had just seen a group of art ad=
visors from Hong Kong in line at the =E2=80=9CHong Kong Cafe.=E2=80=9D

I really wanted to spend some time talking about the Tom Wesselmann retrosp=
ective at the Fondation Louis Vuitton. But there was too much to shoehorn i=
nto this newsletter. I may take some space on Tuesday to discuss that show =
in relation to Wesselmann=E2=80=99s market. It=E2=80=99s interesting.

More to the point, the quality of the shows at the Cartier Foundation, Fond=
ation LV, and Pinault Collection are just beyond belief. There were a lot o=
f great gallery shows in Paris, too. I missed
Ropac=E2=80=99s Sturtevant show, but saw the videos on Instagram over and o=
ver. Despite putting some serious miles on my walking boots each day in Par=
is, I still left feeling like I missed a lot of great art.

One last thing: I just don=E2=80=99t understand why the art coverage in The=
 New York Times is edited with so little regard to its credibility. If I re=
peatedly quoted the same two figures ( https://www.nytimes.com/2024/10/10/a=
rts/design/london-frieze-week.html?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%2810%2F20%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F15%2F24%2=
9&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da4=
2abd12a ) in nearly every report, my editors would take me aside and tell m=
e to find some new sources.

More on Tuesday,
