          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>But first=E2=80=
=A6</i><br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-he=
ight:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-f=
ormat:bullet"><li><i>A quick correction</i>: On Sunday, I wrote that Christ=
ie=E2=80=99s had sold twice as much at auction as Sotheby=E2=80=99s and Phi=
llips, and that Sotheby=E2=80=99s sales figures were in the same neighborho=
od as Phillips, a much smaller company. Those numbers were wrong. Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s sold $56 million worth of art, not $38 million. Sotheby=E2=80=99=
s accounted for 24 percent of the total sales at auction in London; Phillip=
s had 12 percent; Christie=E2=80=99s had 60 percent of the sales; and Bonha=
ms had the remaining 4 percent. <br/><br/>As penance for my sloppy use of p=
ivot tables, let=E2=80=99s acknowledge Sotheby=E2=80=99s preferred measure =
of London sales performance: combined June and October sales totals where
Sotheby=E2=80=99s sold $188.6 million against Christie=E2=80=99s $126 milli=
on. However, if you add in the sales from March, the numbers swing back to =
Christie=E2=80=99s selling $422 million in the comparable auctions to Sothe=
by=E2=80=99s selling $349 million.<br/><br/>If you are a longtime reader, y=
ou=E2=80=99ve noticed that I try to stay away from the market-share battles=
 between houses, because I don=E2=80=99t see how that helps buyers and sell=
ers. The auction houses make their own market share pitches directly to sel=
lers; they don=E2=80=99t need my help. At Wall Power (and its predecessors,=
 Artelligence and Art Market Monitor), my goal has been to gauge the overal=
l market, on one hand, and monitor the individual markets for artists=E2=80=
=94or markets within their body of work=E2=80=94on the other.</li><br/><li>=
<i>Design Miami may have been the big winner in Paris</i>: The standout fai=
r in Paris=E2=80=94the one that <i>everyone</i> seemed to make time for and=
 post about on their Instagram account=E2=80=94was Design Miami.Paris, whic=
h was
held for a second year in the H=C3=B4tel de Maisons, an 18th century pile t=
hat features one of the largest private gardens in the city. The house, own=
ed for generations by a Corsican noble family=E2=80=94the <b>Pozzi di Borgo=
</b>, who trace their roots back to <b>Napoleon</b>=E2=80=94had been divide=
d into apartments many years earlier to house the family=E2=80=99s many des=
cendants. (<b>Karl Lagerfeld</b> maintained a suite of rooms there for 30 y=
ears; he left after the house was sold in 2010 to <b>Ali Bongo Ondimba</b>,=
 the recently deposed president of Gabon.) <br/><br/>On my last night in Pa=
ris, the house came up in conversation at a cocktail party on Rue de Rivoli=
, where the hostess told me that she had lived there years ago with her ex-=
boyfriend, a family member. As grand and sumptuous as Lagerfeld=E2=80=99s r=
ooms were, she told me, the family kept access to the garden for themselves=
, which was ideal, this week, for displaying various objects at Design Miam=
i.Paris, including <b>Jean Prouv=C3=A9</b>=E2=80=99s
demountable <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnV=
DJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTck0ySl9XU21KM05PSkZ2ZXFPST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuaW5zdGFncmFtLmNvbS9wL0RCT2xQemlOUmUyLz91dG1fc291cmNlPWlnX3dlYl9jb3B5X2x=
pbmtcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249V2FsbCtQb3dlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODEwJTJGMj=
AlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxM=
CUyRjE1JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3Vy=
Y2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5=
hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjExNDIyMjF9/41ee80fd2a9a05e49=
5f89a53aebb8f23bfb1525e1d0e02e367ded5bacbedb3b7" style=3D"color:#d40000;tex=
t-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">Carnac house</a></u>, whi=
ch sold during the preview for =E2=82=AC1 million. Another example of Prouv=
=C3=A9=E2=80=99s demountable houses was installed in front of the Grand Pal=
ais at Art Basel Paris, further underscoring the intimate connection betwee=
n the art and design markets. <br/><br/>Indeed, some of the standout object=
s at Design Miami.Paris ride the line between sculpture and furniture: Gale=
rie Mitterrand brought an array of <b>Lalanne</b> works to the fair, with <=
b>Fran=C3=A7ois-Xavier</b>=E2=80=99s surprisingly modern marble-topped dini=
ng table=E2=80=94which, remarkably, featured not a single animal motif=E2=
=80=94receiving exceptional attention. (The Mitterrand display more than ma=
de up for that absence.) A <b>Marc Newson</b>
pod of drawers designed to be a companion to his famous Lockheed Lounge=E2=
=80=94both pieces of furniture resemble the aluminum skin and aircraft rive=
ts of a Lockheed plane=E2=80=94was on offer at Carpenters Workshop Gallery =
for $1 million. That=E2=80=99s a bargain when you consider that an <u><a hr=
ef=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ=
0dTck0ySl9XU21KM05PSkZ2ZXFPST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2hyaXN0aWVzLmNv=
bS9lbi9sb3QvbG90LTQ5MTM2OTU_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkV=
SUyslMjgxMCUyRjIwJTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0=
NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTAlMkYxNSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cd=
TAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJk=
MTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxMTQyMjIyfQ/=
8fce4c327455742532e9b3cd1c8ad7920a212dcaa1ceea5c3b5a8209bb0e83cc" style=3D"=
color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">earlier =
version</a></u> of the pod was sold at auction for $1 million in 2007. <br/=
><br/>But one of the best booths=E2=80=94or rooms, really=E2=80=94was the c=
ollaboration between Galerie Gastou and Galerie Desprez-Br=C3=A9h=C3=A9ret,=
 which displayed the earthy wood-carved furniture of <b>Jean Touret</b>. Ag=
ain, to give you a sense of the intimate connection between design and the =
selling of art, a booth at the Art Basel fair was also furnished with a Tou=
ret bench. Finally, <b>Jeanne Greenberg Rohatyn</b>=E2=80=99s Salon 94,
a prominent Manhattan gallery, was also active from their booth at Design M=
iami.Paris. Greenberg Rohatyn sold several hundred thousand pounds=E2=80=99=
 worth of furniture and vases by <b>Gaetano Pesce</b> and <b>Rick Owens </b=
>at the fair. <br/></li></ul></td>
