         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s4">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The Nahmads=E2=80=
=99 booth featured one of <b>Joan Mir=C3=B3</b>=E2=80=99s series of constel=
lation paintings. (Another in the series got pride of place at the end of t=
he surrealism show at the Centre Pompidou.) The Nahmads were adamant that t=
he painting, which had been bought at auction seven years before for $31 mi=
llion, was not for sale. Meanwhile, Hauser &amp; Wirth conspicuously displa=
yed <b>Kazimir Malevich</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Suprematism, 18th Construction</i>=
 in the middle of their booth, which was bought at auction in 2015 for $33.=
7 million, and which had also been brought to the fair with no advance noti=
ce. One prominent collector told me the best picture at the fair was Landau=
=E2=80=99s <b>Wassily Kandinsky</b> painting, <i>Murnau mit Kirche II</i>, =
which the dealer bought for nearly $45 million early last year and repeated=
ly deflected questions about price with vague
numbers (well into the high eight-figures) until this week, when the work w=
as on the stand but =E2=80=9Cnot for sale.=E2=80=9D One would expect this k=
ind of dealer behavior at Art Basel=E2=80=99s apex event in Switzerland; th=
at it was happening in Paris was a sign that galleries were going all-out t=
o impress potential buyers, and to build anticipation for next year. <br/><=
br/>And yet, perhaps even <i>more </i>important for Paris was the fact that=
 the city=E2=80=99s museums and art foundations pulled out all the stops to=
 mount a wide variety of shows. The best of them, according to Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s <b>James Tarmy</b>, was the knockout retrospective of 92-year-old C=
olombian artist <b>Olga de Amaral</b>, held at the Cartier Foundation for C=
ontemporary Art, which has been housed for 30 years in a glass-box <b>Jean =
Nouvel</b> building deep in the 14th arrondissement. (It will move to anoth=
er Jean Nouvel-designed building in a more central location across from the=
 Louvre next year.) There were also two
encyclopedic surveys: one of Arte Povera at <b>Fran=C3=A7ois Pinault</b>=E2=
=80=99s Bourse de Commerce; and the exhaustive, and a little bit exhausting=
, 100th anniversary of surrealism show at the Centre Pompidou. <br/><br/>Th=
e Arte Povera show had numerous great pieces, but depending on your taste o=
r point of view, just as many or more baffling works=E2=80=94although it al=
so reveals the extent of Pinault=E2=80=99s holdings, which is <i>staggering=
</i>. Meanwhile, the surrealism show lacked a clear thesis. There was so mu=
ch work by so many different artists that it was difficult to see the fores=
t for the trees. At the Mus=C3=A9e d=E2=80=99Orsay, there was a long-overdu=
e celebration of the art of <b>Gustave Caillebotte</b>, a painter better kn=
own to history for his financial and moral support of his impressionist pee=
rs than as the deeply modern artist that he was. The focus on Caillebotte w=
as certainly a fitting way to mark the 150th anniversary in the city where =
impressionism was born.<br/><br/>I cannot
leave the topic of museum shows without mentioning the surprise show of the=
 week: <b>Jackson Pollock</b> at the Picasso Museum. It turned out to be an=
 instructive meditation on the influence of Picasso and his surrealist work=
s on Pollock and his circle in the 1930s, when they were feeling their way =
toward the breakthrough moments of abstract expressionism. <br/></td>
