          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In short, Horowitz =
had many reasons to feel chuffed. An art fair, after all, is about more tha=
n just selling art. For galleries, the sales matter, but they also benefit =
from participating in a great, exclusive fair, which this certainly was. Ma=
ny galleries participate in Art Basel in Hong Kong or Miami in the hopes th=
at, over time, they might earn the right to show in Basel. This year, the P=
aris fair had 195 participating galleries, and a third of them operate spac=
es in France. <br/><br/>Of course, for collectors, a fair like Art Basel is=
 about far more than going home with an invoice for a new painting or sculp=
ture. It is an <i>experience</i>=E2=80=94part reunion, part chance to measu=
re one=E2=80=99s status, part entertainment. And for new collectors, it=E2=
=80=99s an education, a way to take in a lot of art in a short period of ti=
me, to train the eye and learn the
landscape and lingo. But you=E2=80=99ll always feel like an outsider if you=
 don=E2=80=99t buy, because buying art is what gets you invited to the dinn=
ers and the parties. <br/></td>
         </tr>
